{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"517f0114-8ade-47d1-a455-bf069a1959e1","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n**MSTest**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**xUnit**\n```csharp\n[Fact(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\n// or for parameterized tests:\n[Theory(Skip = \"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**NUnit**\n```csharp\n[Ignore(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\n**TUnit**\n```csharp\n[Skip(\"Reason message\")]\n```\n\nAll four will mark the test as skipped/ignored in test results (not failed), and the reason string appears in the test output so your team knows why.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"008a6448-9218-45b5-88cd-0d8ab29f17ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test skip attributes across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit. I have a skill available called `dotnet-test-frameworks` that contains reference data for .NET test framework detection patterns, including skip annotations. Let me invoke it.\n\nWait, the skill description says \"DO NOT USE directly — loaded by test analysis skills\". But the user is asking a direct question about skip annotations. Let me just answer from my knowledge since this is a straightforward factual question.\n\nHere are the skip attributes:\n\n**MSTest**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n**xUnit**: `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]`\n\n\n**NUnit**: `[Ignore(\"reason\")]`\n**TUnit**: `[Skip(\"reason\")]`\n\nLet me provide this concisely.","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"0428:284287:184DEC7:1B98338:69E81E65"},"id":"72358c22-1801-47b0-a683-677ef3a351f4","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:43.240Z","parentId":"d622a84b-ce92-42e7-ace0-3ccb2b4eb1bd"}
